[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    130[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m When validation fails (unverified claims, fabricated citations), the pseudocode sets status to [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mREQUIRES_REGENERATION[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m but doesn't specify what happens next. The implied path is: regenerate the letter. But there's no retry limit and no different strategy on retry. If the model hallucinates the same way on a second or third call (same prompt, same inputs, same temperature), the pipeline enters an infinite regeneration loop. At $0.15-$0.30 per generation call, a loop is cheap per iteration but adds up across thousands of PAs.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    131[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add to Step 7 or "Why This Isn't Production-Ready": "On [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mREQUIRES_REGENERATION[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m, limit retries to 2-3 attempts with a different strategy each time: first retry with temperature=0 for deterministic output, second retry with explicit callouts of the previously-fabricated claims in the prompt ('the following claims were not supported by source facts and must not appear in the letter: ...'), and after 3 failures escalate to human composition rather than continue regenerating. Track retry counts per case in DynamoDB and emit a metric when a case exhausts retries."[K
