[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    146[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Bedrock Knowledge Bases has per-account TPS limits on [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mRetrieve[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m. A practice running end-of-quarter PA batches (common: office staff catching up on pended requests before month close) could fire hundreds of PA workflows in parallel, each issuing multiple KB retrievals. Under burst load these calls will throttle, and the pseudocode has no backoff strategy.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    147[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add a brief note in Step 2 or Step 5: "Knowledge Base Retrieve has per-account TPS limits. For bursty workloads (end-of-quarter catch-up, shift-change batches), implement exponential backoff with jitter on the retrieve calls and consider caching the most frequently-retrieved policies in an in-memory layer or ElastiCache for the duration of a batch run. The top 20 payer/service combinations typically account for 80% of retrievals."[K
